{
  "doc_id": "8004",
  "text": "The results of this study demonstrate the important implications of HIV-transmitted resistance mutations on viral fitness. K65R, in addition to conferring resistance to tenofovir, also leads to significant reductions in viral replication and fitness [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The consequence is a mutation that, according to our findings, is rarely detected even in settings with widespread use of tenofovir, which has been increasingly used as the main NRTI backbone of anti-retroviral regimens in developed countries in the past decade. Though uncommon and despite in vitro antagonism [CITATION_3] , K65R occurred with other mutations that impact viral fitness, including M184V in 35% (7/20) and L74V in 5% (1/20) of K65R-containing sequences.",
